text: Started lasted night. Nice tutorial, so far.  For random number with seed, this is the code (from golang docs):  package main  import (  "fmt"  "math/rand"  "time" )  func main() {     rand.Seed(time.Now().UnixNano())     min := 1     max := 100     randomNumber := rand.Intn(max-min+1) + min     fmt.Println("A random number from 1-100:", randomNumber) }

author: @chrismccullough2607
text: @Sentdex, the current program you wrote for random numbers will produce the same number every time (81). You need to add a line defining the seed above your line with rand.Intn, if you want to have pseudo-random numbers. Such as:   rand.Seed(time.Now().UnixNano())  -- note: this requires the "time" package to be imported   See the following links for more details:   https://stackoverflow.com/questions/39529364/go-rand-intn-same-number-value#answer-39529428   https://stackoverflow.com/questions/8288679/difficulty-with-go-rand-package#answer-8288765

author: @kfsone
text: Food for thought:  You shrugged off editor selection, but in these videos you visibly struggle to work with the language and tools.  1- As a (great!) gen. purpose editor (gpe), sublime doesn't default to being imposing; the golang community is actually intensely strict about layout; most gpes have some form of plugins to bring the language to the editor, 2- For active development, though, it's really worth investing the time to pick and learn an ide; about 30% of this video is spent on you operating your system (e.g "We didn't save it", "If we go here"),  In Python terms: spend 30 minutes getting anaconda, pycharm, vim, emacs or visual studio code set up well in terms of editor and debugger layout and hotkeys, or at the very least have your-editor and ipython open side by side. Developing interactively in Python is a fantastic way to train oneself to practice TDD.

author: @peterst6906
text: For the rand godoc. In math, the notation [0,n) means from 0 to the number, not including the number.   That is, a [ on a set indicates that the number is in the set, whereas a ) on a set indicates the set does not include that number.  So [0,n) as an int, means 0-99
